CANADA DAYBOOK: Bank of Nova Scotia Meeting, Teachers’ Results

-- B y   D a v i d   S c a n l a n
-- 
2011-04-05T05:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-05/canada-daybook-bank-of-nova-scotia-meeting-teachers-results.html
Bank of Nova Scotia (BNS) , Canada’s third-
biggest bank, holds its annual meeting today in Halifax, Nova
Scotia. Chief Executive Officer Richard Waugh says he expects
the lender to meet its annual profit target this fiscal year.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*Canada’s election campaign continues. Prime Minister Stephen Harper pledged to scrap the country’s long-gun registry if re-
elected on May 2, while Liberal opposition leader Michael Ignatieff pledged increased support for veterans.  ECONOMY:
*Nova Scotia Finance Minister Graham Steele presents his fiscal
plan for the year that began April 1, scheduled for shortly
after 1:00 p.m. New York time.  EVENTS:
*Bank of Nova Scotia holds its annual meeting of shareholders in
Halifax, Nova Scotia. 9 a.m. Toronto time.
 *Ontario Teachers’ Pension Plan,   Canada ’s third-biggest
retirement-fund manager, releases its annual results for 2010 at
10 a.m.
* Forzani Group Ltd. (FGL) , Canada’s largest sporting-goods chain, and
oil producer Arcan Resources Ltd. are scheduled to release
fourth-quarter earnings after markets close.
*Hathor Exploration Ltd., which explores for uranium, graduates
to the Toronto Stock Exchange from the  TSX Venture Exchange .
*Jim Bertram, chief executive officer of natural gas marketer
Keyera Corp., is scheduled to address the National Bank
Financial Oil Sands Infrastructure Conference in Montreal.  MARKETS:
*The S&P/TSX rose for a fifth session, gaining 88.2 points, or
0.6
percent, to 14,218.35.
*Yields on two-year Government of Canada bonds fell two basis
points to 1.81 percent.
*The Canadian dollar fell to 96.70 cents per  U.S. dollar  at 5
p.m. yesterday in Toronto.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Scanlan at   dscanlan@bloomberg.net . 